      "kicker": "Symptom",
      "h1": "Gallstone itch – when the itch starts inside",
      "lead": "That stubborn itch that doesn’t match what you see on the skin can feel confusing and exhausting. When it feels deep, diffuse, or worse at night, it’s worth thinking beyond dry skin. Sometimes the signal comes from bile flow, liver stress, or the kidneys trying to tell you something is off.",
      "problemTitle": "Is it really just dry skin?",
      "problemBody": "<p>Itch that feels internal is often described as <strong>systemic itch</strong> – and it behaves differently from ordinary dryness. In conditions such as <em>intrahepatic cholestasis</em>, bile acids and related substances can build up, triggering itch even when the skin looks fairly normal. Bilirubin and other lab markers may be part of the picture, which is exactly why guessing is not enough.</p><p>The usual advice is to moisturize more, exfoliate more, or “cleanse” the skin harder. But when the root cause sits in the bile ducts, liver, or kidneys, pushing the skin harder rarely helps. In fact, over-washing and strong actives can weaken the barrier further and stack irritation on top of an already stressed system.</p><p>You deserve a clearer reading of what your body is doing. If the itch comes with fatigue, dark urine, pale stools, yellowing, swelling, or weight loss, you should seek medical care. We do not diagnose, but persistent itch can be your body’s way of saying: don’t brush this off.</p>",
